result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: The defendant shall not commit any criminal offenses; shall notify the Taylor County District Attorney's Office, as well as the Clerk of Court's office, of any change of address within ten days of said change.  Defendant shall undergo a psychological evaluation and provide proof to the District Attorney Office. Defendant shall successfully complete counseling and provide proof of attendance to the DA's office. Defendant must comply with all counseling and/or treatment as order per the "Deferred Acceptable of a Guilty Plea Agreement" in Eau Claire County Case No. 16CM715 and agree to sign a release authorizing the Eau Claire DAGP Coordinator to share information regarding the defendant's compliance with the Taylor County DA's office.
Defendant must undergo an AODA assessment and follow-through with treatment.

judgments.dispoDesc: Pursuant to an agreement the court granted the state's motion for a deferred entry of judgment of conviction on this charge for a period of one year.  Upon successful completion of the agreement the state will move to dismiss Ct. 1.
